III. The old phraseology of the Romans spoke of free men also

as received by postliminium, namely, if a man went to another city and then returned to his own. Also servants, horses, mules, ships which fell into the enemy's hands, and were then retaken, were reco- vered by postliminium. The later jurists made two kinds of postli- minium: that by which we ourselves return, and that by which we recover anything.

IV. 1 The right exists in war and in peace. In peace, it belongs to those who, when the war breaks out, are among the enemy. Other prisoners of war have not postliminium, except that be agreed upon.
